</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uvallaes.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vallaes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orc Pawn</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/14/01 3:07:48 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/shadeofnight/gungho.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: AO</span><hr size=1> The game is set on the world of Rubi-ka in the far distant future (@29,000 A.D.) and the planet Rubi-ka is &quot;owned&quot; by the hyper-corporation Omni-Tek (OT).  OT basically offered to bring in colonist under indentured servitude, some of the people brought in rebelled at OT's harsh treatment and false promises and became the clans fighting for freedom against OT. OT is basically the evil bad guys and the clans are the good guys. In the middle of this are the neutrals that choose not to get involved with either side.<br>
<br>
What makes AO better than EQ (IMO):<br>
- Ability to buy kits to regenerate health and nanos (mana) at very affordable prices. No BS bandaging to 50% and then needing a healer or long time on your arse. No staring at a spellbook or more sitting on your arse for mana.<br>
<br>
- Soloing is viable, and not just for druids, mages and necros. Pretty much anyone can solo. Some professions definitely have an easier time though.<br>
<br>
- Sci-fi setting that is new and interesting after all the Fantasy settings.<br>
<br>
- Unlimited bank box.<br>
<br>
- Your own personal apartment to store things in and decorate.<br>
<br>
- Ability to buy cars and planes to use for travel.<br>
<br>
- Guns. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   I'm a soldier in AO, so this is definitely a plus in my book.<br>
<br>
- Ability to do missions, so that you can actually sign on and accomplish something in under an hour if you want.<br>
<br>
- Limited PvP, not all zones are PvP and there are enough that you could conceivably never have to fight PvP if you chose not to. But if PvP is your thing there are plenty of zones in fight in as well.<br>
<br>
- List goes on....lots of cool things.<br>
<br>
Like Ankel said it is getting better (bug-wise) everyday.  So far cities are still very laggy, but that is my only real gripe right now...oh and they messed up nightvision goggles in the last patch but I'm sure they'll fix it. They have been steadily patching so it should be good to go soon. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/udreadstar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>dreadstar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Dervish Cutthroat</span><br>  Posts: 170<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/14/01 6:24:43 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: AO</span><hr size=1> Besides everything the others has posted these are some things I like about AO over EQ.  I think for me like Ankel said is true about a flawed AO is = equal to EQ. (This is some what biased in the fact I'm very burnt out of EQ.)<br>
<br>
But these are the things I like about AO:<br>
<br>
Missions.  Any mission can be done solo or if you want you can dupe the key and give it to a friend and do the same dungeon together or with several friends.  3 different kind of missions.  Put a piece into a specific object (fix a radar), assassinate a named npc, get an object and bring it back to the mission generator.  You can select several different things about the mission.  Want it to give more exps then money? or more money then exps?  About 6 customizable selectors.<br>
<br>
Most missions can be finished within an hours time.  And you always get the item you expect.<br>
<br>
Tons of different items/equipment/weapons/nanos (spells)/implants (magical equipment kind of).<br>
Tons of different skills that you can improve on.  Want a tank that can heal pretty well?  You could if you wanted to.  It costs a lot of ips (units of a skill) to be able to.<br>
<br>
Much better graphics and 10x better sound/music.  Even though its so buggy you really have to turn it down until they get it fixed.  Even then the graphics are on par if not a bit better then EQ's are.  The dust storms, lightening, windy rain.  All very impressive.<br>
<br>
No twinking or ebaying.. (even though there are ebayers).  Since each piece of equipment needs a certain amount of skill to use.  So it limits it greatly (good and bad though, I bought a really pretty nice weapon with a loan from a friend.  But couldn't use it for a few levels until I was able to put enough points into each skill that was needed).<br>
<br>
Banks with almost unlimited (must be close to unlimited) spaces for items.<br>
<br>
Even on grey (EQ's green equiv) you still get 1 exps <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Money is only credits.  No little change, that never gets used anyway.<br>
<br>
No corpse recoveries.  Your body after a minute (except for the equipment that's equipped) shows up a unit that you can loot your body from.<br>
<br>
Exps lost is only if you hadn't paid for insurance.  Lets say your out fighting and gain 5k in exps.  You die before you make it back to town to pay for insurance you loose it all.  But lets say you make that much and then make it to town.  May a small fee (depends on your level) and if you were to die you wouldn't loose any unless you've killed some stuff meanwhile.  So it takes some planning on how much your willing to risk.<br>
<br>
Huge world that so far seems pretty different.  I've only been to a handful of zones.  Each seem somewhat unique.<br>
<br>
Transportation, can be done from city to city from whompas (or something like that)  But if you want to travel to more then the places then what the whompas can take you.  You can have a few different classes that can take you on the 'grid'<br>
<br>
Chat client outside of the game, you can login and chat through a web browser to someone who's in the game.<br>
<br>
Maps, it has built in maps for zones that you would be familiar with.  Those that you aren't you can actually buy them and use them if your skill is high enough.<br>
<br>
I'm sure theres more.  Those are the only things that are coming to the top of my head right now.<br>
<br>
But to be honest, my suggestion would be to wait a month or so.  All the bugs right now will slowly tick you off unless you have a *lot* of patients.<br>
<br>
Theres a huge amount of potential.  And with a 4 RL year story line that will make the game very interesting.<br>
